HF.name: Handling Fee

SC.name: Stuffing Charges

ACD.name: Advanced Cargo Declaration
ACD.description: The Advanced Cargo Declaration is a system used to electronically submit detailed information about cargo to customs authorities before the shipment arrives, facilitating efficient processing and enhancing security measures.

AGC.name: Agency Charges
AGC.description: Agency Charges for FCL freight local services cover the fees associated with the professional management and coordination of the shipping process by shipping agents or freight forwarders. These charges encompass a range of services, including documentation handling, customs clearance, port coordination, and regulatory compliance. By leveraging the expertise and networks of these agents, shippers can ensure efficient, compliant, and smooth transportation of their cargo.

AMS.name: Automated/Aquired Manifest System
AMS.description: The Automated/Aquired Manifest System streamlines the process of managing shipment details by electronically capturing and transmitting manifest information to customs authorities, ensuring compliance and expediting the clearance process.

CEF.name: Custom Entry Fee
CEF.description: The Custom Entry Fee is charged for processing and submitting the necessary customs documentation for imported or exported goods. This fee covers the administrative work required to ensure compliance with customs regulations and to facilitate the legal entry or exit of goods.

CMF.name: Container Maintenance Fee
CMF.description: Container Maintenance Fees are charges applied by shipping lines, container depots, or logistics providers to cover the cost of maintaining and repairing shipping containers to ensure they remain in good condition for use in transportation. These fees help to keep the containers safe, functional, and compliant with regulatory standards.

EIR.name: Equipment Interchange Receipt
EIR.description: An Equipment Interchange Receipt (EIR) is a document used in the shipping and logistics industry to record the interchange of equipment, typically containers, between different parties involved in the transportation process. It serves as a receipt and acknowledgment of the transfer of responsibility for the equipment from one party to another.

EXP.name: Export Service
EXP.description: An Export Service refers to a range of services offered to facilitate the export of goods or products from one country to another. These services are typically provided by freight forwarders, shipping companies, customs brokers, and other logistics service providers to assist exporters in efficiently and effectively managing the export process.

FCG.name: Facilitation Charge
FCG.description: "Facilitation Charge" or "FCL (Facilitation Charge for Locals)" is typically a fee levied to cover the administrative and logistical expenses associated with a service. This charge might be applied in various contexts such as transportation, events, legal services, or other administrative processes where coordination and support are required.

HBL.name: House BL
HBL.description: The House B/L fee covers the cost of issuing a House Bill of Lading by a freight forwarder, which serves as a receipt and contract for the transportation of goods at a secondary level, usually under a Master Bill of Lading.

ISC.name: Import Survey Charges
ISC.description: Import Survey Charges refer to fees associated with conducting inspections or surveys on imported goods. These surveys are typically carried out to assess the condition, quantity, and quality of the cargo upon arrival at the destination port. Import surveys help ensure that the goods meet the contractual specifications and that any potential damage or discrepancies are documented.

MCC.name: Manifest Charge
MCC.description: The Manifest Charge summary provides an overview of the fees associated with manifesting cargo for shipment, including documentation costs, handling charges, and any applicable surcharges or adjustments.

RSC.name: Re Seal Charges
RSC.description: Re-Seal Charges cover the cost of replacing seals on shipping containers to ensure security and prevent tampering. This involves removing old or damaged seals and applying new tamper-evident seals.

THC.name: Terminal Handling Charge
THC.description: Terminal Handling Charges are fees levied by port terminals for the loading and unloading of containers from ships, as well as their handling within the terminal.

VGM.name: Verified Gross Mass
VGM.description: Verified Gross Mass (VGM) is a crucial requirement in the shipping industry, particularly for containerized cargo. It refers to the verified weight of a packed container, including the weight of the cargo, dunnage (packing materials), and the container itself. The implementation of VGM is part of the Safety of Life at Sea (SOLAS) regulations, aimed at enhancing maritime safety by ensuring that the weights of containers are accurately reported and handled.

AHFR.name: Agent Handling Fees - Rebate
AHFR.description: Agent Handling Fees - Rebate refers to the fees paid to shipping agents for their services, which may include a rebate or discount for certain services rendered during the shipment process.

GSLC.name: Shipping line All-in charges
GSLC.description: Shipping line all-in charges offer a streamlined and transparent approach to pricing in international shipping. By consolidating various fees and surcharges into a single rate, this model simplifies billing, enhances cost predictability, and reduces administrative complexity. Shippers benefit from having a clear understanding of their total shipping costs upfront, facilitating better financial planning and decision-making. The components of Shipping Line All-In Charges may include the basic charge, terminal handling charges, documentation fees, fuel surcharges, security surcharges, peak season surcharges, port congestion surcharges, currency adjustment factor, container imbalance charges, and war risk surcharges.

ISPS.name: International Ship and Port Facility Security Charge
ISPS.description: The International Ship and Port Facility Security (ISPS) Charge is a fee imposed to cover the costs associated with implementing and maintaining the security measures mandated by the International Ship and Port Facility Security (ISPS) Code. The ISPS Code is an international framework developed by the International Maritime Organization (IMO) to enhance the security of ships and port facilities in response to the threats of terrorism and other security concerns.

LOLO.name: Lift on/Lift off charge
LOLO.description: Lift On/Lift Off (LOLO) charges are essential components of the shipping process, covering the costs associated with loading and unloading containers at ports. These charges include labor costs, equipment usage, and terminal fees for both lifting on and off operations. Understanding and managing LOLO charges are crucial for efficient shipping operations and accurate cost management.

MISC.name: Miscellaneous Fee
MISC.description: The Miscellaneous Fee encompasses various incidental expenses that may arise during the shipping process. These can include administrative costs, small handling fees, or other minor charges not categorized under specific headings.

POCH.name: Port Charges
POCH.description: The Port Charges summary outlines the various fees levied by port authorities for services rendered, including but not limited to terminal handling charges, berth fees, pilotage fees, harbor dues, and any additional surcharges or taxes imposed at the port.

SEAL.name: Seal Charges
SEAL.description: The SEAL charge code in Full Container Load (FCL) freight local services refers to the cost associated with providing and applying seals to shipping containers. These seals are crucial for ensuring the security and integrity of the cargo during transit. The charge covers the procurement of high-quality, tamper-evident seals and the labor required to affix them to the containers. Using seals helps prevent unauthorized access and tampering, thus safeguarding the goods from potential theft or contamination. Understanding and accounting for the SEAL charge is essential for shippers to ensure comprehensive cost management and enhanced security of their shipments.

ADMIN.name: Administration Fee
ADMIN.description: The term "Administration Fee" in the context of "FCL Locals" likely pertains to the fees associated with administrative tasks and services specifically related to Full Container Load (FCL) shipping and logistics for local operations.

ICDHC.name: ICD Handling Charges
ICDHC.description: ICD Handling Charges, or Inland Container Depot Handling Charges, are fees imposed for the handling and processing of containers at an Inland Container Depot (ICD). An ICD is a facility located away from seaports where containers are received, stored, and dispatched for further transportation by road, rail, or inland waterways. These charges cover various services provided at the ICD to facilitate the movement of containers between different modes of transportation and ensure efficient logistics operations.

EXWORKS.name: Ex Works Charges
EXWORKS.description: Ex Works (EXW) charges encompass the costs that a seller incurs to make goods available at their premises for pickup by the buyer. These charges include the product cost, packaging, loading, documentation, and inspection fees. Under EXW terms, the buyer assumes responsibility for all subsequent transportation, export clearance, insurance, and delivery costs.

BL SURRENDER.name: BL Surrender Charges
BL SURRENDER.description: BL Surrender Charges are fees for surrendering the original Bill of Lading to the shipping line, allowing the consignee to receive the cargo without needing the physical document at the destination port.

These charges cover various services provided at the ICD to facilitate the movement of containers between different modes of transportation and ensure efficient logistics operations.

EXWORKS.name: Ex Works Charges
EXWORKS.description: Ex Works (EXW) charges encompass the costs that a seller incurs to make goods available at their premises for pickup by the buyer. These charges include the product cost, packaging, loading, documentation, and inspection fees. Under EXW terms, the buyer assumes responsibility for all subsequent transportation, export clearance, insurance, and delivery costs.

BL SURRENDER.name: BL Surrender Charges
BL SURRENDER.description: BL Surrender Charges are fees for surrendering the original Bill of Lading to the shipping line, allowing the consignee to receive the cargo without needing the physical document at the destination port.
